:"about 1153–Deceased","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1185–Male":"1185–Deceased","1878–Male":"1878–Deceased","1153–Female":"1153–Deceased","Abt 1153":"about 1153","6 Jul 1878":"6 July 1878","Abt 1185":"about 1185","1153":"1153","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","1878":"1878","Stackpold, Pembroke, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Ireland","Stackpole, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Stackpole, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Howard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the Middle English personal names <i>Huward</i> (also <i>Howard</i>) and <i>Heward</i>, from Old French <i>Huard</i> (itself from ancient Germanic <i>Hugihard</i>, <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, understanding, spirit’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, bold’). As <i>Hugh</i> appears in Middle English as both <i>How</i> and <i>Hew</i>, this is the definite origin of <i>Heward</i> and a source of <i>Howard</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. See   Hugh  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Haward</i> or <i>Howard</i>, usually an Anglicized form of Old Danish <i>Hāwarth</i> (Old Norse <i>Hávarthr</i>, from <i>há</i> ‘high’ + <i>varthr</i> ‘guard, guardian, warden’). Alternation between <i>Haward</i> and <i>Howard</i> may have led to later confusion with   Hayward  .","English: occasionally a variant of   Ewart   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Fogarty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, James Patrick, Kieran, Seamus, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Fógartaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Fógartach</i>’, a personal name from <i>fógartha</i> ‘proclaimed, banished, outlawed’. It is sometimes Anglicized as   Howard  ."]},{"name":"Huggard","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the medieval personal name <i>Hugard</i>, a variant of <i>Huard</i> (see   Howard  ). This surname is also established in Ireland (Kerry)."]},{"name":"Heward","meanings":["English: variant of   Howard  ."]},{"name":"Hayward","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>hayward</i> ‘keeper of the hedges and enclosures’ (Old English <i>hēgweard</i>), a manorial officer in charge of the common fields who protected corn and hay from cattle, theft, or damage, and supervised the harvest.","occasionally a variant of   Howard  ."]},{"name":"Huard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aime, Adelard, Jacques, Jean-Pierre, Lucien, Marcel, Alcide, Amiee, Armand, Aurele, Clermont, Fernard.","French and Channel Islands (Jersey): from the Old French personal name <i>Huart</i>, either identical in origin with   Howard   1 or a pet form of Old French   Hue  .","History: Jean Huard from Courson-Monteloup in Essonne, France, married Anne-Marie Amiot in Quebec City, QC, in 1670."]},{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"Slackpole","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Welsh: habitational name from Stackpole (Pembrokeshire), apparently named with Old Norse <i>stakkr</i> ‘stack’ + <i>pollr</i> ‘pool’, referring to a stack of rocks on the coast at the entrance to Broadhaven. The name was taken to Ireland and adapted by settlers of Norman descent, where it is recorded in Dublin as early as 1200. The name has been Gaelicized as <b>de Stacapúl</b>; the family was also known in Irish as <b>Galldubh</b> ‘dark stranger’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stackpoole","meanings":["English (Cheshire) and Welsh: variant of   Stackpole  ."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Greek: Same as Catherine."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Greek: Pure."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Catherine Howard Slackpole was born about 1153, in Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with De Stackpole."},"et":{"Abt 1153–":"umbes 1153–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1878–Male":"1878–Surnud","1153–Female":"1153–Surnud","Abt 1153":"umbes 1153","6 Jul 1878":"6. juuli 1878","Abt 1185":"umbes 1185","1153":"1153","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","1878":"1878","Stackpold, Pembroke, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Iirimaa","Stackpole, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Stackpole, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1153–":"noin 1153–Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1185–Male":"1185–Kuollut","1878–Ma